title: Grateful Dead Live at Rich Stadium on 1992-06-06
lineage: Cassette Master (Nakamichi CR-7A) > Tascam DA-3000 (DSF 1-bit/5.8 MHz) >KORG AudioGate 4 > Samplitude Pro X3 Suite > FLAC/24
description:
Set 1

Touch Of Grey-> Greatest Story Ever Told, Althea, It's All Over Now, Friend Of The Devil, When I Paint My Masterpiece, Ramble On Rose, Let It Grow

Set 2

Iko Iko, Estimated Prophet-> The Same Thing-> He's Gone-> Drums-> Jam-> The Other One-> The Wheel-> Throwing Stones-> One More Saturday Night, E:Baba O'Riley-> E: Tomorrow Never Knows

"Take A Step Back," between Masterpiece and Ramble On

reviews.review_text:
First set This is the first time I've ever got to hear the soundboard of the first set.  I was at the show on the floor with my first wife and a couple of friends.  It was pretty crazy.  That minute and a half of dead(no pun intended) air after FoTD was clearly them discussing the crowd surging forward.  It was hot, we were packed in like sardines and some guy pissed on the one of the mats covering the field right in front of us.  Yet that first set is etched in my mind as the best set I got to see in my short 25 show stint.  
The second set?  Well, it was all too much for my wife, who had to bail out at the set break before totally freaking out and naturally my first obligation was to make sure she was alright.  We knew we wouldn't get back down to that spot on the floor, roughly 75-100 feet from the stage so I just tried to find a place where she would not feel claustrophobic.  However, it felt like a mass of humanity everywhere we turned.  I eventually let her make the call and we left.  It was the right call, of course.  
Listening back on this 26 years to the day later and it's a microcosm of my entire Dead experience.  Some ups, some downs and some incredible music.  Jerry and Bob were in peak form with both seemingly trying to one up the other.  That first set ends in a powerful rendition of Let it Grow, but I think they both battled to a draw.  It was the most in sync I ever saw the two of them.
Thanks for posting.

Bold in Buffalo '92. I grew up in upstate New York. Like a lot of deadheads, most of my early Grateful Dead education came from actual educators. High school English teachers to be exact. Affectionately known by the students as Chap-dog (the Phish enthusiast who still catches Bobby and Trey any chance he gets) and Stur-bob (the Garcia/Dylan/Seinfeld/Hitchcock aficionado who retired to the Carolinas). After the workday was done and the final bell rang, these two could sometimes be found with a couple of other faculty members and students chatting about the Grateful Dead scene past and present. Tapes were loaned. CDs gifted. One subject I distinctly remember coming up multiple times was Rich Stadium. 

Chap-dog once asked, “remember those Orchard Park shows when the first set would be in the daylight and the second set would be in the dark?” Turns out, Stur-bob’s first show was 7/4/86. When you look back, they had some huge shows at that venue, a couple of which still stack up as “legendary”. They never played a bad show there. While Dead & Company’s touring days were done, if they wanted to play a one-off East Coast show, Orchard Park would be a great place for it. Central to the Northeast, Midwest, and Canadian fans.

After rolling across the runway and getting the propellers going with shows in Sacramento and Las Vegas, 6/6/92 is when the Summer Tour seemed to take off in earnest. It’s a very interesting show. It starts off piping hot, with Phil’s bass cranked up louder than I’ve ever heard it for a ripping Touch of Grey that crisply segues into Greatest Story Ever Told. Then, barring a neat Stones cover, the first set mainly sticks with slower songs, some of which (Althea) work much better than others (Ramble on Rose). 

The second set is good gravy. Estimated Prophet doesn’t blast you away like other versions, but it folds perfectly into a sick Same Thing for a double helping of Bobby. Very unlikely, unexpected, and well-executed segue. He’s Gone is as rich and heavy as you’d hope from a 1992 version. The Drums > Space > The Other One takes you far out, and there’s a definite Spanish Jam hidden in those murky depths. He’s Gone, The Other One and The Wheel all harbor some really enjoyable cosmic vocal effects. Healy up to his old tricks? A couple of Bobby rockers and a gooey Baba > Beatles encore wrap things up nicely. Estimated through the Wheel is the meat and potatoes of this show. There are miscues and slow spots elsewhere, but also definite highlights, making this one a rollercoaster that keeps your ears perked throughout. Lots of fun to listen to rolling around Pennsylvania waiting for Hot Tuna's show at the Sherman!

This is a perfect, polished soundboard. What’s interesting about this recording is that it picks up bits of the band members communicating to each other through the new system which allowed them to rechannel their vocal microphones so that they were speaking into each other’s ear monitors. I think they first tried this during the Cal Expo run. It’s fun to hear them call out the next song, count off, or ask for more of this or less of that from the sound crew. Somehow, this recording picks some of that stuff up, and it’s a neat peak behind the scenes.

There's a cool Liquid Blue t-shirt out there specifically designed for this show.

All in all, a proper Vince-era summer tour Dead show where they keep you guessing and fire up some strong moments.
